  "response": "There are several complex geopolitical factors that contribute to the different dynamics between India-Pakistan and China-India relations:\n\n1. Military and Economic Capabilities\n- China has significantly larger military and economic power compared to India\n- China's military budget is much higher than India's\n- China has more advanced military technology\n\n2. Border Situation\n- India-China border disputes exist, but are less volatile compared to India-Pakistan tensions\n- Border regions are mostly mountainous and less populated\n- More diplomatic engagement between China and India\n\n3. Strategic Positioning\n- China sees India as a potential economic partner and competitor, not a primary security threat\n- Pakistan serves as a strategic ally for China against India and in the region\n\n4. Historical Context\n- India-Pakistan conflict stems from partition and religious differences\n- China-India tensions are more about territorial and economic competition\n\n5. Nuclear Capabilities\n- Both China and India have nuclear weapons, creating a strategic balance\n- India-Pakistan nuclear dynamics are more unpredictable\n\nThese factors contribute to the different threat perceptions between the countries. China views its relationship with India through a more pragmatic lens of strategic competition, while the India-Pakistan relationship remains more emotionally charged.",
